laboratory work</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2008-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Francis Crick Institute</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:description>sex determination in birds</gtr:description><gtr:id>2BC8B35E-4630-4FA6-8241-0A9B4BA621D5</gtr:id><gtr:impact>publications</gtr:impact><gtr:partnerContribution>discussions, laboratory work, funding applications</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>discussions, laboratory work, funding applications</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2012-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Our demonstration of cell autonomous sex identity (CASI) in birds has overturned a long-standing dogma that the vertebrate sexual phenotype isimposed by hormone action. We were also the first group to demonstrate that birds possess a system of 'dosage compensation' that operates to equalise the phenotypic effects of characteristics determined by genes on the sex chromosomes. Our research also resolved the centuries-old question regarding the nature of gynandromorph birds. 
Our finding strongly reinforce recent suggestions that, in humans and other mammals, certain behaviour patterns and disease susceptibilities are hormone-independent and result from cell autonomous factors. Eventually this is likely to underpin major elements of 'personalised medicine'. 
A spin-off from our research has lead to the development of an in-ovo sexing assay that is currently under assessment by the poultry industry. If applied, this procedures will lead to significant increases in food production.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>EEA40480-5B0B-4A71-A04D-54B37492F496</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have demonstrated that male and female cells respond differently to extracellular signals (hormonal and developmental). We have identified a set of genes that are expressed differently in male and female cells from the point of fertilisation through to adulthood. These genes are expressed in a sexually dimorphic fashion in all tissues at all stages of development, and are likely to represent the molecular signature underlying the inherent sex-identity that we identified in avian cells. Here we show that this inherent sex-identity can be 'short-circuited' by perturbing intracellular signals. Most significantly, we demonstrate that cells of the male and female immune sustems are different: female cells are effectively pre-primed to respond to infection possibly accounting for the sex-related differences seen in mortality rates due to infection.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>We have further developed our in-ovo sexing assay to fully meet the timing and cost requirements of the poultry industry. If this assay can be successfully applied, this procedures will lead to significant increases in food production.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>B35D3A9C-B5EC-43E1-A1BE-C04F77870CE5</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:res